[normal]A roadmap for coal[bold]A major potential benefit from CCS deployment
[normal] will be to secure the long
[normal]-
[normal]term future for UK coal mining
[normal] and its 9,000 employees.
[normal] 
[normal]Without investment in CCS there is no long term future for the UK coal industry. 
[normal] 
[normal]Actions taken now to invest in CCS 
[normal]and reform our electricity market can secure this core industry in a low carbon economy for the long term. Delays will drive investment and dependency on gas fired power without resolving the challenge of CO2 capture, whilst losing a once-only opportunity 
[normal]for global leadership in the vital CCS industry. 
[normal]The UK mines 
[normal]in 2012 mined 
[normal]over 1
[normal]7
[normal] million tonnes of coal a year, and 
[normal]its 
[normal]coal power stations generate over 
[normal]38%
[normal] of the UK’s electricity
[normal] 
[normal]compared with 
[normal]28
[normal]% from gas generators. At peak times, we turn to the e
[normal]xceptional flexibility of coal power for up to 50% of our electricity supply. Coal 
[normal]currently 
[normal]directly provides over 
[normal]5
[normal],000 jobs in deep and surface mines and ancillary functions, whilst coal power stations employ over 4,
[normal]000
[normal] staff, many in skilled quality em
[normal]ployment. 
[normal]The government should therefore develop a roadmap for UK coal mining alongside its EMR implementation plan, to provide security for UK coal investors and its workforce.
[normal]What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific[bold] and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome? [bold]The
[normal] 
[normal]main barrier to developing CCS 
[normal]in this period 
[normal]appear
[normal]s to be the slow 
[normal]formation and implementation of government energy policy
[normal] to su
[normal]pport CCS
[normal]. The 
[normal]two key strands of government support for 
[normal]are EMR reforms and the CCS commercialisation programme. These two processes must work in parallel
[normal] 
[normal]to ensure the maximum momentum and technological advance. 
[normal]G[bold]overnment’s Electricity Market Reform (E[bold]MR)[bold]The EMR includes 
[normal]measures
[normal] to support all low-carbon generation with Contracts for Differences (
[normal]CfDs
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal]providing for 
[normal]deployment of CCS in the power sector. 
[normal]Key tests for the EMR if it is to drive CCS investment include: 
[normal]The EMR has so far failed to provide clarity in any of these t
[normal]hree areas. 
[normal]The draft 
[normal]EMR 
[normal]Delivery Plan
[normal] 
[normal](July 2013) is unhelpful in its range of zero to 12GW of CCS by 2030, with 
[normal]even 
[normal]the upper limit almost half of the ambition set out by the Committee on Climate Change, of 18-20GW by 2030.
[normal]The delivery plan says: 
[normal]“B
[normal]a
[normal]sed on central demand and decarbonisation assumptions (100g CO2/KWh) 
[normal][the scenario] 
[normal]illustrates a generation mix that would be consistent with CCS costs and deployment circumstances being favourable compared to other technologies. In this scenario, three C
[normal]CS plants are built by the end of 2020, with commercial deployment of both gas and coal CCS throughout the 2020s- leading to deployment of around 12 GW CCS in 2030.
[normal]”
[normal]CCS commercialisation programme[bold]The latest CCS Commercialisation Programme is tasked with 
[normal]launching a process to ensure the general deployment of CCS for coal and gas by the 2020s. 
[normal]From an early commitment to four CCS projects, currently there may be support for only one or two. As a bare minimum, the government should rapidly conclude negotiat
[normal]ions at 
[normal]Drax
[normal] and Peterhead, with a view to plant
[normal] being operational
[normal] by 2018 at the latest. 
[normal]More than that, the government should retain its commitment to four demonstration projects and consider returning to other projects under development, offering them 
[normal]clear and speedy alternatives either through the CCS competition or via 
[normal]CfDs
[normal]. Sustained deployment is critical at this stage.
[normal]Is the UK Government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of CCS in the UK?[bold]The government’s 
[normal]approach lacks the necessary pace and scale. As noted above, currently the main drivers of CCS are reliant on effective government policy. The two key strands of government support for CCS are the EMR reforms and the CCS commercialisation programme. These 
[normal]two processes must work in parallel, not sequentially, to ensure the maximum momentum, technological advance and robustness of the programme against possible future project cancellations.  At present there is a strong perception that the government is resi
[normal]sting further CCS deployment until the commercialisation projects are underway.
[normal]Could the successful development of CCS improve international efforts to mitigate climate change? What role could UK CCS play in this? [bold]Yes. CCS is acknowledged to be a crucial transitional technology for climate change mitigation. The UK has a crucial seedbed role to play, although there is a now a clear danger that other countries will move ahead more rapidly, so that the UK loses techno
[normal]logical and market leadership. 
[normal]In Canada, the Boundary Dam
[normal] CCS project has been completed, a 110 MW coal pow
[normal]e
[normal]r plant with 
[normal]retrofit 
[normal]CCS technology
[normal] due to start operating in 2014. The total cost of the project is estimated to be $1.24 billion, with $240 mi
[normal]llion from the federal government in 2011, of which about $180 million has already been spent. The provincial government is also supporting the project. Employment includes 20 at the R&amp;D stage
[normal], peak
[normal] construction employment of 1,500 and 41 operational emplo
[normal]yees. 
